docs.abstract: Some factories are firing up again, but with many workers quarantined and parts in short supply, production is limited.
docs.snippet: Some factories are firing up again, but with many workers quarantined and parts in short supply, production is limited.
docs.lead_paragraph: Airbus is slowly restarting its assembly line in China. General Motors began limited production on Saturday. Toyota followed on Monday morning.

headline.main: Slowed by the Coronavirus, China Inc. Struggles to Reopen
headline.print_headline: China’s Factories, Immobilized By Disease, Struggle to Reopen

docs.abstract: The virus outbreak has rattled the global economy, disrupting supply chains and closing off access to a lucrative consumer market.
docs.snippet: The virus outbreak has rattled the global economy, disrupting supply chains and closing off access to a lucrative consumer market.
docs.lead_paragraph: The coronavirus outbreak in China has rattled the global economy, disrupting virtually every major industry, from food, fashion and entertainment to automobiles and technology.

headline.main: From Starbucks to FedEx, Coronavirus Upends Businesses That Depend on China
headline.print_headline: Virus’s Effect on Commerce Ripples Out

docs.abstract: Amazon is hiring aggressively to meet customer demand. Traffic has soared on Facebook and YouTube. And cloud computing has become essential to home workers.
docs.snippet: Amazon is hiring aggressively to meet customer demand. Traffic has soared on Facebook and YouTube. And cloud computing has become essential to home workers.
docs.lead_paragraph: OAKLAND, Calif. — While the rest of the economy is tanking from the crippling impact of the coronavirus, business at the biggest technology companies is holding steady — even thriving.

headline.main: Big Tech Could Emerge From Coronavirus Crisis Stronger Than Ever
headline.print_headline: Big Tech May Emerge Stronger Than Ever

byline.original: By Daisuke Wakabayashi, Jack Nicas, Steve Lohr and Mike Isaac
